rComments: He is really the worst teacher I've ever had. We got really far behind the scheduled materials but still gonna be tested on them. You won't learn anything new from this class if you have him as your prof. Even he himself get the concepts wrong sometimes. Avoid at all cost. I learned half of the materials and still is getting only B's.

If you have to push chem back a semester to avoid this class, by all means, do it.  Even if you do well in the course grade-wise, you may not grasp the material from this guy.  College is expensive, and you will not get your moneys-worth from him.

The class is 3 weeks behind on material,quizzes are on things not covered yet & you either get a C or F, his exams are horrible, he's a terrible lecturer, and he only curves exams if the average is an F. Worst of all is that he just doesn't seem to care. I expected this class to be challenging. I did not expect the professor to be so disappointing.

As an MCB student, I am used to challenging classes. However, Jamieson is not only hard but inconsistent and unprepared. He lacks experience and has significant trouble writing exams. He violates his class policy to suit his own mistakes without announcing it to the class. I have never been so disappointed in the Chem department.

Whatever you do, don't get stuck with this professor. He apparently has his doctorate, but it does not show in his teaching style- so if you have him, definitely study a ton on your own and look at old exams for practice. Maybe try going to Hummel's lectures because Jamieson doesn't even use the iClicker for attendance.

What a turn-off. Completely useless. Ask him a question, he'll give you an answer, but ak him the same question 5 minutes later, he'll tell you the diametric opposite. I don't know how he managed to convince the University to hire him.

He is the worst teacher I have ever had. I studied for exams for hours and still did poorly. If you want to do well in this class you should have a prior knowledge of Chemistry or expect to teach yourself. He is intelligent, but needs to learn to communicate information to students in ways we can understand.
Students are not provided with PowerPoint slides or any notes besides whatever he writes on the board in lecture. Makes it really hard to learn the material.

It's no joke, this is the worst lecturer I have ever laid eyes on.  Within the first couple weeks, he started falling behind in material.  Lectures are over-simplified, showing only basic examples.  Yet he also talks about advanced concepts which are useless.  Almost every test question comes out of left field.  Avoid him.

Intelligent man, just not very good at teaching. Very slow, class was behind all semester. Not a clear speaker, makes alot of mistakes throughout lecture. You are better off not attending  lecture; read the book, do practice problems, ask TAs for help. Exams and quizzes are difficult and not curved.

I think he's trying, but his teaching methods just aren't working for me. He is approachable enough in office hours. Try to get someone more experienced because there are no practice tests available yet because he is brand new. Poor clarity. Curves tests if lower than 65% average. Expect to teach yourself.

Not a helpful professor. Must learn how to teach more efficiently and translate material to students better. He acts like we're already chemists and understand his lectures. He lacks clarity in response to questions. Moreover, his tests contain information not previously taught in lecture.

I'm sure he's a great chemist, but he is a terrible professor. The quizzes are designed for everyone to fail (you can only get 5/10, 7.5/10, 10/10, or a 0) because he believes they should be a "learning tool". Tests are difficult. You will be **frequently** tested over material that he hasn't yet covered or won't cover at all.

This guy can't even spell and shouldn't be teaching a class; he makes a mistake on nearly everything he writes. I think he knows what he is doing but he can not teach at all.  Tests were difficult and quizzes were on material not covered anywhere. Also had us doing homework on things not even covered yet.  He needs to rethink teaching...and fast.
His exam is so hard. Once he went back to home for family emergency. When we knew he will come back soon, everyone cried because the substitute professor is so good. Her name is Tina Huang.
